Based on my research, here is a comprehensive answer to your question about UXP async/background processing capabilities in Premiere Pro.

---

## Direct Answer

**Yes, you can make async API calls while the user continues editing - UXP does NOT block the UI.** This is a fundamental architectural improvement over the previous ExtendScript/CEP approach.

### Key Points:

1. **UXP method calls are asynchronous and do not block the UI thread** - Unlike ExtendScript where all calls were synchronous and blocked Premiere's UI, UXP calls are non-blocking.

2. **Single JavaScript engine, but non-blocking execution** - UXP runs in its own non-blocking thread within the same process as the host application. The UI rendering uses native controls (not Chromium), which is more performant.

3. **Network requests (fetch) can run in background** - You can run network requests and timers entirely in the background, outside of any edit operation.

4. **Property access is synchronous by design** - For ease of migration from ExtendScript, property getters/setters are synchronous and don't need `await`, though they're asynchronous under the hood.

---

## Limitations and Caveats

| Limitation | Description |
|------------|-------------|
| **Background code can slow host app** | Running code in background is discouraged as it can make the host application slow |
| **Read-only access during background ops** | Background code may see incorrect intermediate state if running during other async operations |
| **No Web Workers** | UXP does not support Web Workers for true multi-threading |
| **No C++ Hybrid plugins yet** | Premiere Pro doesn't yet support UXP Hybrid plugins for computationally heavy C++ tasks (planned for future) |
| **HTTP vs HTTPS bug** | Known issue in Premiere 25.6.3 where HTTP requests fail (HTTPS works) |

---

## Code Examples

### Basic Async Fetch Pattern

```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`);
    }
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(data);
    return data;
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Fetch error:", err);
  }
}

// Call without blocking - user can continue editing
fetchData().then(result => {
  // Update UI with result
  updatePanel(result);
});
```

### Manifest Configuration for Network Access

```json
{
  "requiredPermissions": {
    "network": {
      "domains": [
        "https://api.example.com",
        "https://*.yourservice.com"
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

### Non-Blocking Timer Pattern

```javascript
// setTimeout is available in UXP
function pollForChanges() {
  setTimeout(async () => {
    const status = await checkStatus();
    if (!status.complete) {
      pollForChanges(); // Continue polling
    } else {
      updateUI(status);
    }
  }, 1000);
}
```

### Accessing Premiere API (Async Methods)

```javascript
const ppro = require("ppro");

async function getProjectInfo() {
  // Method calls are async and non-blocking
  const project = await ppro.Project.getActiveProject();
  const sequences = await project.getSequences();

  // Properties are synchronous (no await needed)
  const projectName = project.name;

  return { projectName, sequences };
}

// This runs without blocking the UI
getProjectInfo().then(info => {
  console.log(`Project: ${info.projectName}`);
});
```

### Parallel Async Operations

```javascript
async function loadMultipleResources() {
  // Run multiple fetches in parallel - UI remains responsive
  const [userData, settingsData, templatesData] = await Promise.all([
    fetch("https://api.example.com/user").then(r => r.json()),
    fetch("https://api.example.com/settings").then(r => r.json()),
    fetch("https://api.example.com/templates").then(r => r.json())
  ]);

  return { userData, settingsData, templatesData };
}
```

---

## Threading Model Summary

```
+--------------------------------------------------+
|              Premiere Pro Process                 |
|                                                   |
|  +------------------+    +--------------------+   |
|  |   Premiere UI    |    |    UXP Plugin      |   |
|  |   Main Thread    |    |   (Own Thread)     |   |
|  |                  |    |                    |   |
|  |  - Timeline      |    | - JavaScript V8    |   |
|  |  - Preview       |    | - Native UI        |   |
|  |  - Panels        |    | - async/await      |   |
|  |                  |    | - fetch API        |   |
|  +--------+---------+    +----------+---------+   |
|           |                         |             |
|           +----Native API Bridge----+             |
|             (No string passing)                   |
+--------------------------------------------------+
```

---

## Official Documentation Links

- [The Premiere UXP API - Main Documentation](https://developer.adobe.com/premiere-pro/uxp/)
- [Understanding UXP APIs](https://developer.adobe.com/premiere-pro/uxp/resources/fundamentals/apis/)
- [Premiere API Reference](https://developer.adobe.com/premiere-pro/uxp/ppro_reference/)
- [UXP Premiere Pro Samples (GitHub)](https://github.com/AdobeDocs/uxp-premiere-pro-samples)
- [UXP Arrives in Premiere - Adobe Blog](https://blog.developer.adobe.com/en/publish/2025/12/uxp-arrives-in-premiere-a-new-era-for-plugin-development)
- [Network Recipes - InDesign UXP (applicable patterns)](https://developer.adobe.com/indesign/uxp/resources/recipes/network/)
- [Sync/Async - XD UXP Documentation](https://developer.adobe.com/xd/uxp/develop/plugin-development/javascript-and-xd/sync-async/)
- [executeAsModal - Photoshop UXP (for comparison)](https://developer.adobe.com/photoshop/uxp/2022/ps_reference/media/executeasmodal/)

---

## Best Practices for Non-Blocking Operations

1. **Use async/await consistently** - Adobe recommends async/await over raw Promises
2. **Avoid long-running synchronous loops** - Break them up with `setTimeout` or `requestAnimationFrame`
3. **Use Promise.all for parallel operations** - Maximizes efficiency without blocking
4. **Keep background operations minimal** - Excessive background code can slow Premiere
5. **Handle errors gracefully** - Network failures shouldn't crash the plugin
6. **Use the UXP-optimized library** for rendering long lists efficiently: [adobe/uxp-optimized](https://github.com/adobe/uxp-optimized)
